		<td class="main_font" width="100%">


								
								
			<!-- Begin News/Information Section -->
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" ID="Table23">
					<tr id="trmasthead">
						<td valign="middle" class="main_font" align="center">
							<font size="3"><b>&nbsp;</b></font>
					    </td>
					</tr>
					
					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Diggo's Master Fletching Tips</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:ronjaffe@bellsouth.net">Diggo McDiggity</a> | 
		            2/1/2000 2:37:34 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">You may be asking why a Druid would take up fletching since he will never be able to use the bows or arrows that he makes, but I decided to embark on the skill for several reasons.<BR>
<BR>
First of all, it's one of the few trade skills where one can actually generate an income. If you've ever examined baking, you will see what I mean. <BR>
<BR>
Secondly, my other characters use bows and why pay retail when they can buy &quot;direct?&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Lastly, fletching (at the moment) does not require killing anything or involve any other character to raise your skill. It's much safer to buy arrow parts than to kite Crag Spiders in East Karana if you have ever been hunting spider silk. Besides as a Druid, I've already got Wisdom and Intelligence..might as well use them for something other than mana.<BR>
<BR>
Here are some tips I learned along the way. Your mileage may vary depending upon your race, intelligence, wisdom, and roll of the dice as you strive for the magical 200 number.<BR>
<BR>
1. Fletching takes time and is tedious. Learn the CTRL-CLICK method of fletching to save as much hair on your head as possible. Read other posts if you don't know what I mean.<BR>
<BR>
2. The term &quot;Master&quot; at 100 is really not entirely correct as Master implies being able to do anything well and trust me, you don't want to try high-end Oak or Darkwood bows at skill level 100. Master would be more appropriate at skill level 175 when one can expect a 1/2 ratio of successes on darkwood bows. Skill 100 would be better considered a &quot;Journeyman&quot; for lack of a better term.<BR>
<BR>
3. Increase your fletch skill with arrows and not bows. Your fletch skill will improve at the same rate with 2 silver fletches as it does with 40 plat fletches. Besides, 5 failures at 2 silver each comes out to alot less than 5 failures at 40p each.<BR>
<BR>
4. Find a good place to fletch. The best place I have found to fletch is Surefall Glade. As a small zone, the lag is minimal. If you have ever had to fletch in East Commons or South Karana or any other big zone, you will know what I mean. Lag can drive you nuts.<BR>
<BR>
5. Your stats - This is the most important determiner as to the success of your fletches. Intelligence affects the rate at which your skill increases and Wisdom affects the number of successes. Lastly, your charisma affects the prices that you pay for supplies and sell back to the merchants. <BR>
<BR>
As a Druid Halfling, my charisma was 50 which means that I would pay as much as 70plat more for a darkwood staff. I invested money on a gradual basis for a backpack of charisma items. Now with charisma of 100 I can buy and sell at a good price which is important when you hit the magic fletch skill number of 162 - See Below.<BR>
<BR>
6. Plan out fletching sessions. You will never get to master if you don't allocate time to just sit and fletch. I think in total it took me about 10 real-life hours or more to reach skill level 200. After the magic number, 162, I would allocate an hour a day until I got there. If you can make it to Surefall Glade, even better, it will be faster fletching, although the druids that just stand their have to keep buffing themselves with SOW, barbcoat and all that other nonsense, so you might have to turn off your speaker.<BR>
<BR>
7. Take a break every once in a while. Surefall glade is a safe place to get up, go pee, have a snack, rest your arms and neck   :)<BR>
<BR>
8. Fletch with the least expensive components needed to raise your skill. Heres the most important thing to remember. You all hopefully know that the cheapest combination of arrows is Large Nock, Round Fletch, Wood Shaft, Field point. Every combination of arrows needed to raise to skill level of 200 uses 3 of the 4 cheapest components. For example, the arrows used to raise to skill level 200 after the last trivial break of 162 is, Silver Tip (Was Bladed) Wood Shaft, Round Fletch, Large Nock.<BR>
<BR>
9. Sell back to your merchant - Dont count on selling any of the arrows you make to other players. The reality is the arrows you fletch to raise your skill get exponentially more expensive but their stats dont really increase. Players want cheap arrows with good range and you won't be making those because they won't help your fletch skill at a higher level. If you want to take a break and make a bow or two to sell, go right ahead. Let players know that you are a fletcher and can make bows. Selling bows even slightly above cost to other players while you learn will help generate some income considering the money you will lose learning to fletch.<BR>
<BR>
10. Charisma is critical - You will sell 10,000 or more arrows back to the merchant during the course of your study. The higher charisma you have the less you pay for parts AND the more they pay you for arrows so each fletch attempt involves 2 times that you will  spend money...once for buying parts, once for selling finished arrows. If you consider that a couple gold lost per fletch can add up to hundreds of plat during your mid-skill-level study you will see that you want to get your parts as cheaply as possible and sell the arrows for as much as possible.<BR>
<BR>
Get some jewelry or whatever it takes to raise your charisma to at least 100. As I said, mine was 50 and I had to switch between my intelligence/wisdom jewelry and my charisma jewelry each time I bought and sold. It made my advancing take alot longer (and was a pain in the ass, frankly) but it cost me much less in the long run. A Crude Stein is an inexpensive item that adds 15 charisma for example.<BR>
<BR>
11. Lastly... The magic number, 162...<BR>
<BR>
As you progress through your skill level you will find your getting from about 100-150 takes as long as it did to get from 1-100. Getting from 150-175 is that much longer and the 8 points from 190-198 is awful and the last two points from 198-200 seems... well, you can get the picture. <BR>
<BR>
At skill level 162, that is the last trivial point so the arrows you make from 163 will be the same up to skill level 200. That combination as stated earlier is Bladed/Silver tips, Wood shafts, Round Fletch, Large Nock - This combination means that each fletch will cost you almost 5 plat pieces.. Yeah, no kidding it's expensive, especially when you fail.<BR>
<BR>
But here's the good news. If your intelligence and Wisdom is high enough to successfully complete 18 out of 20 fletches, and your charisma is at least 100, you can actually make money by selling the completed arrows back to the merchant. While making money isn't really the goal it sure makes up for all the money flushed during the failed attempts. I was making about 3 plat per stack of 20 arrows sold back to the merchants. Since fletches are so expensive at this level the extra profit will help fund the rest of your fletch study to level 200.<BR>
<BR>
I hope this has helped some of you. If you ever have questions, please feel free to ask. If you are on the Tribunal server. Give me a tell.<BR>
<BR>
Safe journey's and good fletching to you all!<BR>
<BR>
Diggo McDiggity<BR>
22/Druid/Halfling<BR>
200 Skill Master Fletcher<BR>
Tribunal Server<BR>
<BR>

